• forward a copy of the corresponding reply of the DepEd, once available, to determine the latter’s final disposition on the matter;

• direct the MHRMO and the various sections/ department heads to determine the respective needs for JO and contract of services personnel within their sections/departments and consider the utilization of accomplishment reports and Strategic Performance Management System (SPMS) including Job Orders and COS charged to SEF to determine relativity of the renewal of their contract; and

• direct the Municipal Legal Officer to determine the possible legal or legitimate remedies of the Municipality on the approved plantilla positions created under SEF despite the fund’s restrictions on the allowable positions.

We reiterated prior years’ recommendation and Management agreed to -

(i)	exercise due diligence in the performance of duties and responsibilities especially in the implementation of major infrastructure projects taking into consideration the limitations in the utilization of the resources of the Municipality;

(ii)	refrain from procuring and implementing projects unless all permits, clearances and licenses were properly secured from the government authorities to prevent delays in the implementation and other related problems;

(iii)	direct and ensure that implementing sections/offices comply with RA 9184 by conducting detailed engineering on all projects based on the feasibility or preliminary engineering study conducted which establishes the technical viability of the project and conformance to land use and zoning guidelines prescribed by existing laws to prevent any legal impediments during the implementation stage and imposition of curative remedies in correcting past actions/decisions; and

(iv)	submit the legal basis which allows the utilization of SEF on the (a) reclamation component of the Limay By-Pass and Sports ground Projects, specifically the   backfilling works done for the planned sports field/ground and other planned infrastructure projects/civil works; and (b) xxx.

We recommended and the Management agreed to –
include in the Executive Order specific personnel assigned as Accountable Officers for Drugs and Medicines, Office Supplies, Welfare Goods and other supplies, as applicable, to establish clear cut responsibilities and functions to be executed by them;
provide stockroom for the supplies to prevent unauthorized access and to safe keep the supplies and materials;
instruct the BAC Chairperson to ensure that all the required information on the PO are properly/correctly filled out and the GSO to guarantee that all the terms and conditions stated in the PO are complied or fulfilled by both parties;
direct the Municipal Accountant to –
require the requesting departments and committees involved in the procurement process of goods that all the necessary details in the PO and DV’s supporting documents are correctly stated before submitting the mentioned documents for processing of payment;
assign a staff who will be responsible in the preparation and maintenance of SLCs which shall be per type/ class and compute the cost of each item using moving average method (except for drugs and medicines with expiration period);
attach corresponding SSMI with RIS as supporting document in adjustment of expensed portion of inventory accounts; and
reconcile quarterly the physical inventory of supplies with the Supplies Ledger Cards and control accounts and any discrepancy/ies shall be immediately verified and adjusted;
require the Municipal Treasurer to apply for the fidelity bond of Inventory Custodians who are regular employees of the Municipality;
instruct the GSO to –
request for the racks and provide label for the various supplies to organize arrangement and easier monitoring of available stocks;
establish the accountability of each and every inventory custodian to prevent spoilage/wastage of government resources;
properly guide and inform the Inventory Custodians/AOs to update SCs and prepare SSMI to be submitted every week or at least once a month to the Municipal Accountant together with RIS or equivalent document so that issuances will be computed and recorded by the latter; and
conduct physical count of inventory items by type semestrally and report in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
direct the Municipal Health Officer to (i) request from the DOH and PHO documents showing the actual amounts of drugs and medicines transferred to them; and (ii) ensure that all drugs and medicines donated by other agencies are reported to the Municipal Accountant’s Office by furnishing copy of delivery receipts and/or Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) for recording and valuation; and
instruct the Inventory Committee to –
conduct the actual physical count of office supplies, food supplies, drugs and medicines and other supplies to be witnessed by the Auditor or his/her representative;
ensure the preparation of RPCI with complete details in the required format signed by the required signatories; and
cause  the submission thereof to the Audit Team on or before the prescribed period.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to –
specify the duties and responsibilities of the members of the Inventory Committee included in the Executive Order No. 13, Series of 2022 in order to aid the members of the Committee in the discharge of their duties related to the entire process of inventory taking;
direct the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Office (GSO) to complete the details included in the Lapsing Schedule and RPCPPE, respectively, to keep detailed record, facilitate reconciliation and proceed to necessary adjustments, if needed;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) classify asset items as Machinery and Equipment; Furniture, Fixtures and Books; and Other Property, Plant and Equipment with individual cost of at least ₱15,000.000 and a life of more than one year to be recognized as Property, Plant and Equipment; and (ii) consider analyzing various rehabilitation projects, in coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Engineer to properly classify either as assets or expenses in accordance with IPSAS and to present the actual financial performance of the Municipality based on proper matching of revenues and expenses;
direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile records pertaining to the Land account maintained by both Offices and to facilitate the recording of the parcels of land already transferred under the name of the LGU based on Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT);
instruct the GSO to be guided in the procedures included in Section 7 of COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 pertaining the procedures related to One-Time Cleansing of PPE Accounts;
refrain from paying taxes which should have been paid by the seller/s or owner/s of the property or properties as part of its prudence in managing the meager resources of the Municipality; and
instruct the Municipal Information System Officer (MISO) to conduct extensive inspection of the CCTVs installed to identify specific issues/ defects and resolve as soon as possible for these to function based on intended purpose – for public safety and security.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to –
debit the Construction in Progress account when recording the accumulated cost or other appropriate value of land improvements/ infrastructure assets/ buildings and other structures/ leased assets/ leased assets improvements still in the process of construction or development. Credit this account for reclassification to the appropriate Land Improvement/ Infrastructure Asset/ Buildings and Other Structures/ Leased Assets/ Leased Assets Improvements account upon completion;
debit the Advances to Contractors account when recording the advances to contractors as authorized by law and credit this account for recoupment of advances;
submit the lacking perfected MOA/Trust Agreement for the funds received such as DENR - Implementation of Ecological Solid Waste Management and DA RFO III - Procurement of Brand-new Hauling Truck under Enhanced KADIWA Marketing Logistics Support for Inclusive Food Supply Chain Program to determine the use/purpose of the amounts received;
submit to the Audit Team a copy of the liquidation reports duly received by the source agency together with its supporting documents; and
record the following adjusting entries under the Trust Fund books related to the projects Multi-Purpose Evacuation Center and construction of Proposed Child Care Development Center.

We also recommended and the LCE agreed that the –
BAC Secretariat ensure that all procurements undertaken by the Procuring Entity are properly documented as prescribed by RA No. 9184;
Heads of the implementing/monitoring offices, such as – the Municipal Engineer, as the head of the infrastructure arm of the Municipality and the BAC Chairperson, and the MPDO, who monitors and provides aid in the implementation of projects (i) require the submission of the DOLE-approved CSHP and monitor its implementation; (ii) guarantee the inclusion of billboard/signage as one of the pay items and its posting to conspicuous place of the construction site/location for all infrastructure projects to promote transparency; (iii) ensure the timely submission of the perfected contracts, including the supporting documents to facilitate the review and evaluation of the technical aspects of the projects; and (iv) submit certified true copies of approved Work Suspension Order (WSO), Work Resumption Order (WRO) and/or Contract Time Extension (CTE) issued to contractors, for infrastructure projects with delays in implementation to determine the actual cause if justifiable, otherwise, enforce the liquidated damages as set forth by RA No. 9184;
Municipal Treasurer refrain from issuing checks to representative/s of construction company/companies without the authorization from the registered owner/s; and
Municipal Accountant  –
record the (i) 10% retention fees using Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable account; and (ii) 15% mobilization fee using Advances to Contractors account;
maintain subsidiary ledgers to the Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable and Advances to Contractors for ease in monitoring the payments of payables and recoupment of mobilization or advances to contractors; and
include as documentary requirements the (i) DOLE-approved CSHP for infrastructure projects and photo documentations related to the pay item, “Safety, Health and Environmental Requirements”; (ii) proof of posting of billboards; and (iii) certificate from the Insurance Commission regarding the Insurance Company’s authority to issue the bond/security for contractors which opted surety bond as security as part of the documentary requirements in compliance with the relevant DOLE and COA rulings and RA No. 9184.

We recommended that Management:
organize a LCCAP Core Team;
conduct trainings and seminars for the LCCAP Core Team;
conduct in coordination with PENRO a survey, mapping, and planning to determine the updated status of the forest cover of the Municipality;
draft, approve and implement an updated LCCAP incorporating tree planting activities.
revise its 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan to incorporate COVID-19 waste management plan;
fast track the construction of the Municipality’s sanitary land-fill;
intensify IEC programs, focusing also on COVID-19 related wastes;
improve Barangay MRFs, to include facilities for COVID-19 related wastes;
pass an ordinance banning the use of unnecessary single-use plastics at the Municipality Offices and other waste reduction ordinances;
improve the construction of its sanitation vault in accordance with HCWM; and
organize the people scavenging at the transfer station for orientation on proper garbage sorting, provision of equipment, and livelihood support to lessen their health risk and make them partners instead in solid waste management.

We recommended that Management:
designate or assign a Local Population Officer;
include the designated or assigned Local Population Officer in the GAD Committee;
incorporate in the GAD, programs to supplement sex education in Department of Education (DEPED) modules with the use of interactive forms of communication; and
incorporate in the GAD other responsible parenthood and reproductive health programs to address that teenage pregnancies.

4.5       We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
(a) Require the Limay Tourism Council to submit liquidation report and supporting documents for the expenses on the 2018 cultural activities;
(b) Remind the Acting Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to (i) recognize future cash advances for special purposes as Advances for Operating Expenses and (ii) strictly monitor the status of cash advances for timely liquidation thereof;
(c) Impose sanctions on Accountable Officers who unjustly failed to liquidate their cash advances.

We reiterated prior year’s recommendations and Management agreed to:

adopt the control measures in the receipts, issuances, recording and inventory of supplies and materials to protect the resources of the agency against risk of loss, theft and wastage as well as the proper procedures in inventory taking and the rendering of complete and accurate inventory reports;

require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to coordinate for the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in recording supplies and materials to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials;

ensure the immediate filling up of the Supply Officer position and prompt action for additional manpower for the maintenance of records and custodianship of inventories; and

require the Municipal Accountant to thoroughly examine the transactions for the proper charging of expenses to the appropriate accounts.

We reiterated previous year’s recommendations that management –

formally put into writing the verbal agreement of the Municipality to BGH to enable the offsetting of payable and receivable accounts;

determine all the possible actions that can be instituted for the collection of receivables;

pursue the creation of a committee to investigate the whereabouts and verify existence of debtors/borrowers. Hence, management may opt to request for write off of the accounts and seek the approval of the Commission on Audit through submission of the required supporting documents to justify the request; and

set up the Allowance for Doubtful Account.
